R Capstone Project: Did Jason Sudeikisâ€™ Actions After the European Championship Affect the Number of Google Hits About Ted Lasso?

There were mixed reactions to Britainâ€™s loss to Italy in the European Championship this past July, but the most notable were the racist attacks against three of Britainâ€™s players. In response, American actor Jason Sudeikis, who plays the American football coach turned British soccer coach on the AppleTV+ original Ted Lasso, wore a custom shirt that showed his solidarity with the three players to the Ted Lasso season 2 premier. In this project, I want to explore whether Sudeikisâ€™ choice of clothing boosted the google hits for his show in both the United States and Britain.

For this project, we will need the gtrendsR package, installed and added to the package library below:

install.packages("drat")       
drat:::add("ghrr")            
install.packages("gtrendsR")   
 library(gtrendsR)

data("countries")

The first datasets I want to explore is the general interest overtime and by state/region for both keywords Ted Lasso and Jason Sudeikis in both the US and Great Britain. At first glance, it looks like the timing of Sudeikisâ€™ commentary (July 15) was associated with a small spike in hits for Ted Lasso in Britain, but Jason Sudeikis in the US.

ted_lasso_US_inq <- gtrends(keyword = "Ted Lasso", 
        time = "today 1-m", 
        geo = "US")

ted_lasso_GB_inq <- gtrends(keyword = "Ted Lasso",

Next, I will put together a dataframe of the general interest over time in both topics for both the US and Britain.

interest_df <- bind_rows(jason_GB_inq$interest_over_time,
                         jason_US_inq$interest_over_time,
                         ted_lasso_GB_inq$interest_over_time,
                         ted_lasso_US_inq$interest_over_time)

To visualize the trends for both keywords in both the US and Britain, I created a faceted line graph using ggplot2.

interest_viz <- interest_df %>%
                ggplot(aes(x = date, y = hits)) +
                facet_grid(cols = vars(geo)) +
                geom_line(aes(color = keyword)) +
                labs(title = "Hits for Each Keywords in the US and Britain", y = "Hits", x = "Date")
                



interest_viz

Per the visual, there was a spike in hits for Ted Lasso in Britain the day of Sudeikisâ€™ commentary (July 15), but it was not as big as the spike in hits that came the day of the Ted Lasso season two premiere (July 23). The spike in hits for Jason Sudeikis in Britain corresponds to an interview that was televised in Britain on July 26.

Sudeikisâ€™ commentary instead produced a spike in hits for his own name on July 15 and the show on July 23. The spike for his name on August 5-7 could be attributed to other causes, such as interviews done in the US or his appearance on the cover of GQ magazine.

Though we can probably extrapolate the effects of each search term on the other through these visuals alone, I created a linear regression model for each country. In order to do that, I will have to break apart interest_df and recombine it to get the dataframes that will work with a linear regression.

Our null hypothesis: There is no effect on the hits for Ted Lasso when hits for Jason Sudeikis increase.

interest_GB_sudeikis <- interest_df %>%
              filter(geo == "GB", keyword == "Jason Sudeikis") %>%
              rename(keyword_sudeikis = keyword, hits_sudeikis = hits)

interest_GB_lasso <- interest_df %>%
              filter(geo == "GB", keyword == "Ted Lasso") %>%
              rename(keyword_lasso = keyword, hits_lasso = hits)
         
interest_GB <- bind_cols(interest_GB_lasso$keyword_lasso,
                         interest_GB_sudeikis$keyword_sudeikis,
                         interest_GB_lasso$hits_lasso,
                         interest_GB_sudeikis$hits_sudeikis)

              rename("hits_lasso" = "...3", 
                     "hits_sudeikis" = "...4")
              
interest_US_sudeikis <- interest_df %>%
              filter(geo == "US", keyword == "Jason Sudeikis") %>%
              rename(keyword_sudeikis = keyword, hits_sudeikis = hits)

interest_US_lasso <- interest_df %>%
              filter(geo == "US", keyword == "Ted Lasso") %>%
              rename(keyword_lasso = keyword, hits_lasso = hits)

interest_US <- bind_cols(interest_US_lasso$keyword_lasso,
                         interest_US_sudeikis$keyword_sudeikis,
                         interest_US_lasso$hits_lasso,
                         interest_US_sudeikis$hits_sudeikis)

Takes a breath ok, done. Now, letâ€™s create some linear models

model_US <- lm(hits_lasso ~ hits_sudeikis, data = interest_US)

According to the summary, both models have p-values greater than 0.05, which for me signals that we cannot reject the null hypothesis. This in mind, letâ€™s see what a linear regression graph would look like for both.

model_US_viz <- interest_US %>%
                ggplot(aes(x=hits_lasso, y=hits_sudeikis)) +
                geom_point() +
                geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
                geom_smooth(se = FALSE, color = "blue") +
                labs(title = "Correlation between Hits for Jason Sudeikis and Ted Lasso in the US", x = "Ted Lasso", y = "Jason Sudeikis")

model_US_viz
`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

model_GB_viz <- interest_GB %>%
                ggplot(aes(x=hits_lasso, y=hits_sudeikis)) +
                geom_point() +
                geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
                geom_smooth(se = FALSE, color = "blue") +
                labs(title = "Correlation between Hits for Jason Sudeikis and Ted Lasso in Britain", x = "Ted Lasso", y = "Jason Sudeikis")

model_GB_viz
`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Because most of the values of the values for the hits for Jason Sudeikis are zero and there are between one and three outliers, the linear correlation is pretty much non-existant. From these graphs, it is also difficult to tell whether there would be a linear correlation even if Jason Sudeikis got more hits per day.

In conclusion, the British were more interested in what Jason Sudeikis had to do with Britain, so they looked up his show, and people in the United States were more interest in Jason Sudeikisâ€™ racial commentary, so they looked up what happened on July 15. Having lived in the U.S. for all of my life, this behavior among Americans seems typical. Also, when the hits for Ted Lasso increase, the hits for Jason Sudeikis do not. If one day Jason Sudeikis was more recognizable, or if Ted Lasso itself became more famous as a show, I would like to try to rerun this simulation. Perhaps then there would be a correlation.
